</section>



<section xml:id="multi-qubit-bra_ket" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
     <title>Multi-qubit Bra-ket Notation</title>

    <p> We can also combine two independent qubits into a 2-qubit bra-ket notation.
    For an individual qubit, it has two possible outcomes: 0 or 1. For a pair of qubits, 
    we have each combination of possible outcomes - both 0, the first 0 and second 1, the 
    first 1 and the second 0, or both 0. The tricky part is how to calculate the probability of 
    those combined events from the single qubit probabilities. This is when our independent 
    probability calculations come into play - you just multiply the appropriate values together.
    </p>

    <p><image source="L5.3.1to2qubitsbraket.png" width="30%" /></p>

<p> Put in some questions here with 2 qubits and 3 qubits - can grab from my homeworks.</p>

</section>



<section xml:id="bra_ket_state_simplification" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
     <title>Bra-Ket State Simplification</title>

<p>Just like with fractions, there are multiple ways of expressing the same state. Every time 
a state is calculated, we then simplify the state into its preferred form. Let's learn a 
few simplification rules!</p>

<p> The most important rule is that you can multiply all terms by the same number and the 
resulting state is the same; the comparison of the states is what matters, 
not the absolute values. However, the purpose of bra-ket notation is to be easily able to 
tell visually what the probabilities are (and still be able to perform operations). 
Therefore, we have norms in how we express them.</p>

<p> 1. The order of the outcomes is always in increasing numeric order 
(starting with all 0’s and ending with all 1’s). Below is a properly formed 
3-qubit state.  </p>

<p> 2. You may omit any term whose probability is 0.
(make image of:  all four states here ==> 50/50 00 vs 11)
</p>

<p> 3. If all outcomes are the same probability some people omit the leading term. 
However, none of the answers in this book use this rule because it hides the true probability.
(make image of: 50/50 vs no terms in front)</p>

<p> 4. The state with all 0's is never in negative phase </p>

<p>
(make image of something with 00, 11 being negative, 01, 10 being negative ==> 
state with 00, 11 being positive and 01, 10 being negative)  </p>

<section xml:id="vector_state" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
     <title>Vector Quantum Representation</title>

<p>
The purpose of vector notation is to allow us to calculate the output of quantum gates.
Vector notation loses some of the explicit information in bra-ket notation - namely, the
information about what each probability amplitude is tied to. Instead, we have to remember
the proper order.
</p>

<p> Bra-ket notation is always sorted by the value in the ket - the sorting order is, 
from left to right, smallest to largest. Vector notation uses the same order - smallest to 
largest - but it is depicted from to bottom.</p>

 <p><image source="L5.3.brakettovector.png" width="30%" /></p>

 <p> Here are some examples: </p>


 <p><image source="L5.3.brakettovectorexamples.png" width="30%" /></p>

 <p> You have to be careful, though, to express bra-ket notation in the proper order.
 If the bra-ket order is incorrect, then you might accidentally put the terms in the wrong
 locations in the vector. </p>

 <p><image source="L5.3.wrongorder.png" width="30%" /></p>


</section>



<section xml:id="vector_state_simplification" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
     <title>Vector State Simplification</title>

<p> Generally, the state simplification rules are the same for vectors and for bra-ket notation,
with one major exception - you can never remove a state! You must retain the 0. </p>

<p> 1. The order of the outcomes is always in increasing numeric order 
(starting with all 0’s and ending with all 1’s). This is even more important for vector
notation because we don't explicitly write the outcome. </p>

<p> 2. You may NOT omit any term whose probability is 0. (make this text bright red!!)
</p>

<p> 3. If all outcomes are the same probability, people rarely omit the leading term. 
They do, however, factor out a common fractional component and put that in front of the vector.
 (make "rarely omit" red text, plus the last sentence)
</p>

 <p><image source="L5.3.pullfactor.png" width="30%" /></p>

<p> 4. The state with all 0's is never in negative phase </p>



</section>

    </section>    
    </section>